ave been food riots in Central China. A quarter of a million refugees have streamed into Peiping from a \"distressed\" countryside. Food riots in the southern province of Kwangtung. At the same time there has been reporting food shortages in various parts of the country, deep cuts in rations, the closing of communal messhalls--in 1958 the sign of supply difficulties--and, in a few instances, disease and death from malnutrition.\n\nFood shortages are normal in China in the spring, and the Chinese Communists, for all their fulsome claims of bumper harvests, have clearly not eliminated this annual problem. While the food situation this spring is decidedly tight in most places and probably grim in some, there is little to substantiate a belief that it is markedly worse this year than in the immediate past. The 1959 grain harvest was some 10 percent below the good 1958 harvest, but the regime has managed to keep a very tight lid on food consumption and probably holds sufficient stocks to sustain diets at least at minimal levels until the early harvest in June", "token_count": 192, "token_end_0based": 191, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "i the communist bloc food supplies tight in communist china there have been food riots in central china a quarter of a million refugees have streamed into peiping from a distressed countryside food riots in the southern province of kwangtung at the same time there has been reporting food shortages in various parts of the country deep cuts in rations the closing of communal messhalls in 1958 the sign of supply difficulties and in a few instances disease and death from malnutrition food shortages are normal in china in the spring and the chinese communists for all their fulsome claims of bumper harvests have clearly not eliminated this annual problem while the food situation this spring is decidedly tight in most places and probably grim in some there is little to substantiate a belief that it is markedly worse this year than in the immediate past the 1959 grain harvest was some 10 percent below the good 1958 harvest but the regime has managed to keep a very tight lid on food consumption and probably holds sufficient stocks to sustain diets at least at minimal levels until the early harvest in june", "unred_source_page": 6}
